# Load the Fashion-MNIST data from tensorflow datasets library

def load_data():
    (x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = tf.keras.datasets.fashion_mnist.load_data()
    x_train = x_train.astype('float32') / 255 #normalising images so values betwene 0 and 1
    x_test = x_test.astype('float32') / 255
    # convert labels to categorical samples
    y_train = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes=10) # changes y_train into a 10 columns array representing classes each with binary values 
    y_test = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes=10)
    return ((x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test))

(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = load_data()
x_train = x_train.reshape((-1, 28**2)) # flattening each 28 by 28 pixel image into  784 features
x_test = x_test.reshape((-1, 28**2)) # flattening each 28 by 28 pixel image into  784 features

class MLP():
    def __init__(self, sizes, epochs, l_rate):
        self.sizes = sizes 
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.l_rate = l_rate
        # we save all parameters in the neural network in this dictionary
        self.params = self.initialisation()

    def leaky_relu(self, x, derivative=False):
        if derivative:
            return  np.where(x < 0, 0.01, 1)
        return np.where(x < 0, x*0.01, x)

    def softmax(self, x):
        # Numerically stable with large exponentials
        exps = np.exp(x - np.max(x, axis=1).reshape(x.shape[0], 1))
        return exps / np.sum(exps, axis=1).reshape(x.shape[0], 1)

    
    def cross_entropy_loss(self, y, y_pred, derivative = False):
        if derivative:
            return  y_pred - y # look at [1] in refernces to see the derivation 
        return -np.sum(y*np.log(y_pred), axis=1)/float(y_pred.shape[0])

    def initialisation(self):
        '''Implements Glorot initialisation'''
        # number of nodes in each layer
        input_layer=self.sizes[0] # dimension of the input
        hidden_1=self.sizes[1] # number of neurons of the hidden layer 1
        hidden_2=self.sizes[2] # number of neurons of the hidden layer 2
        hidden_3=self.sizes[3] # number of neurons of the hidden layer 3
        hidden_4=self.sizes[4] # number of neurons of the hidden layer 4
        hidden_5=self.sizes[5] # number of neurons of the hidden layer 5
        output_layer=self.sizes[6] # number of classes
        np.random.seed(123)
        params = {
            'W1':np.random.randn(input_layer, hidden_1) * np.sqrt(2. / (hidden_1 + input_layer)),
            'W2':np.random.randn(hidden_1, hidden_2) * np.sqrt(2. / (hidden_1 + hidden_2)),
            'W3':np.random.randn(hidden_2, hidden_3) * np.sqrt(2. / (hidden_2 + hidden_3)),
            'W4':np.random.randn(hidden_3, hidden_4) * np.sqrt(2. / (hidden_3 + hidden_4)),
            'W5':np.random.randn(hidden_4, hidden_5) * np.sqrt(2. / (hidden_4 + hidden_5)),
            'W6':np.random.randn(hidden_5, output_layer) * np.sqrt(2. / (output_layer+hidden_5)),
            'B1':np.zeros(hidden_1,),
            'B2':np.zeros(hidden_2,),
            'B3':np.zeros(hidden_3,),
            'B4':np.zeros(hidden_4,),
            'B5':np.zeros(hidden_5,),
            'B6':np.zeros(output_layer,)
        }
        return params

    def forward_propagation(self, x_train):
        params = self.params

        # input layer activations becomes sample
        params['A0'] = x_train

        # input layer to hidden layer 1
        params['Z1'] = np.dot( params['A0'], params["W1"]) + params['B1']
        params['A1'] = self.leaky_relu(params['Z1'])

        # hidden layer 1 to hidden layer 2
        params['Z2'] = np.dot(params['A1'],params["W2"]) + params['B2']
        params['A2'] = self.leaky_relu(params['Z2'])
        
        # hidden layer 2 to hidden layer 3
        params['Z3'] = np.dot(params['A2'],params["W3"]) + params['B3']
        params['A3'] = self.leaky_relu(params['Z3'])
        
        # hidden layer 3 to hidden layer 4
        params['Z4'] = np.dot(params['A3'],params["W4"]) + params['B4']
        params['A4'] = self.leaky_relu(params['Z4'])
        
        # hidden layer 4 to hidden layer 5
        params['Z5'] = np.dot(params['A4'],params["W5"]) + params['B5']
        params['A5'] = self.leaky_relu(params['Z5'])

        # hidden layer 5 to output layer
        params['Z6'] = np.dot(params['A5'], params["W6"]) + params['B6']
        params['A6'] = self.softmax(params['Z6'])

        return params['A6']

    def backward_propagation(self, y_train, output):
        '''This is the backpropogation function for calculating weights and biases. I used derivation in [3] 
        to work out my back propogation method. This MLP model has 6 kernel variables and 6 bias variables.'''
        params = self.params
        change_w_and_b = {}

        # Calculate W6 update
        error = self.cross_entropy_loss(y_train, output, derivative =True) /256
        change_w_and_b['W6'] = np.dot(error.T, params['A5']).T # how come no divide by m
        change_w_and_b['B6'] = np.sum(error, axis=0)
        
        # Calculate W5 update
        error = np.dot(error, params['W6'].T) * self.leaky_relu(params['Z5'], derivative=True)
        change_w_and_b['W5'] = np.dot(error.T, params['A4']).T
        change_w_and_b['B5'] = np.sum(error, axis=0)
       
        # Calculate W4 update
        error = np.dot( error,params['W5'].T) * self.leaky_relu(params['Z4'], derivative=True)
        change_w_and_b['W4'] = np.dot(error.T, params['A3']).T
        change_w_and_b['B4'] = np.sum(error, axis=0)
       
        # Calculate W3 update
        error = np.dot( error, params['W4'].T) * self.leaky_relu(params['Z3'], derivative=True)
        change_w_and_b['W3'] = np.dot(error.T, params['A2']).T
        change_w_and_b['B3'] = np.sum(error, axis=0)
        
        # Calculate W2 update
        error = np.dot(error,params['W3'].T) * self.leaky_relu(params['Z2'], derivative=True)
        change_w_and_b['W2'] = np.dot(error.T, params['A1']).T
        change_w_and_b['B2'] = np.sum(error, axis=0)
        
        # Calculate W1 update
        error = np.dot(error, params['W2'].T) * self.leaky_relu(params['Z1'], derivative=True)
        change_w_and_b['W1'] = np.dot(error.T, params['A0']).T
        change_w_and_b['B1'] = np.sum(error, axis=0)

        return change_w_and_b

    def update_network_parameters(self, changes_to_w_and_b):
        'Updates the network parameters using the SGD update rule'
        for key, value in changes_to_w_and_b.items():
            self.params[key] -= self.l_rate * value

    def compute_accuracy(self, x_val, y_val):
        '''This function does a forwrad pass and checks if the class in the prediction is equal 
        to the true class of a each point in the x_val and then computes the accuracy.'''
        output = self.forward_propagation(x_val)
        pred = np.argmax(output, axis=1)
        predictions= np.count_nonzero(pred == np.argmax(y_val, axis=1))
        return predictions/y_val.shape[0]
    
    def compute_loss(self, x_val, y_val):
        '''Computes cross entropy loss between predictions and true target.'''
        output = self.forward_propagation(x_val)
        return np.sum(self.cross_entropy_loss(y_val, output), axis=0
    
    def iterate_minibatches(self, inputs, targets, batchsize):
        ''' This function splits and returns the inputs and targets as mini batches list. The inputs and targets are 
        randomly shuffled with the same permutation so that our mini batch gradient descent becomes SGD. [2] 
        in refernces explains SGD in more detail.'''
        indices = np.random.permutation(len(inputs)) #generate a random permutation
        x_train_batches = []
        y_train_batches = []
        for start_idx in range(0, len(inputs) - batchsize + 1, batchsize):
            excerpt = indices[start_idx:start_idx + batchsize] 
            x_train_batches.append(inputs[excerpt])
            y_train_batches.append(targets[excerpt])
        return x_train_batches, y_train_batches
        
    def train(self, x_train, y_train, x_val, y_val, batch_size=256):
        '''Train the model using stochastic gradient on minibatches of size 256'''
        accuracies = []
        losses = []
        for iteration in range(self.epochs):
            x_train_batches, y_train_batches = self.iterate_minibatches(x_train,y_train,batch_size)
            for x_batch,y_batch in zip(x_train_batches,y_train_batches):
                output = self.forward_propagation(x_batch) # get predictions for current epoch
                changes_to_w_and_b = self.backward_propagation(y_batch, output) # workout new weighst and biases
                self.update_network_parameters(changes_to_w_and_b)
            epoch_accuracy = self.compute_accuracy(x_val, y_val)*100 #turning validation set accuracy into percentage accuracy
            accuracies.append(epoch_accuracy)
            epoch_loss=self.compute_loss(x_val, y_val) # validation set cross entropy loss at current epoch
            losses.append(epoch_loss)
        return accuracies, losses

A lower rate means more training time and is increased computation cost. The

For the learning rate of 0.1, the loss and accuracy don't converge for training and test sets as we increase the number of epochs. The model is overfitting to the training data. Hence this learning rate is too high.

For the learning rate of $10^{-5}$ is too low, the accuracy of the model on very low and the loss is high and decreases linearly with the number of epochs. Although the loss and accuracy of the model don't converge for training and test sets, I believe this is because 40 epochs are not large enough for the model to converge for such a small learning rate.

The best out of the three learning rates tried was $10^{-3}$ as implemented in Task 1.1.1. This learning rate leads to a low cost (decreases polynomially, very fast to begin and then starts to level off) and high accuracy (increases polynomially, very fast to begin and then starts to level off) as the number of epochs increases. The accuracy and loss do also converge for training and test sets.

(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = tf.keras.datasets.fashion_mnist.load_data()
x_train = x_train.astype('float32') / 255
x_test = x_test.astype('float32') / 255

# Reshaping each image into dimensions (1, 28, 28, 1)
x_train = x_train.reshape((x_train.shape + (1,)))
x_test = x_test.reshape((x_test.shape + (1,)))

My network has a input layer, 5 hidden layers in total (of which the first 4 are convolutional layers and the last is a fully-connected layer), followed by the output layer with 10 neurons (one for each class).Regarding the hidden layers: all convolutional layers apply 3 3 filters, but the first two use 8 feature maps and the last two use 16 feature maps (also called channels). The last convolutional layer is followed by a 2 2 maximum pooling layer. The fully-connected layer has 64 neurons, and is followed by the output layer with 10 neurons.

I am using LeakyReLU(x) with a slope of 0.01 for x < 0 as your activation function between all layers, and the softmax function as the activation function on the output layer.

My optimisation method is stochastic gradient descent (SGD), the loss function is (categorical) cross-entropy.

I will train my model on batches of 256 data points with a learning rate of $10^{-3}$ for 40 epochs.

In [22]:
model1 = Sequential([
    Conv2D(8, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
    Conv2D(8, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
    Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
    Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
    MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(64, activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
    Dense(10, activation="softmax")
])
# Compile The Model
model1.compile(optimizer=SGD(learning_rate=0.001, momentum=0), loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
# Fit And Evaluate The Model Using Validation Dataset
history1 = model1.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=40, batch_size=256, validation_data= (x_test, y_test), verbose=0, shuffle=True)

The loss and accuracy achieved after 40 epochs are similar to in Task 1.1.1. However, it is worth noting that, the CNN is a more efficient algorithm than in Task 1.1.1 as it reduces the loss and increases the accuracy faster for smaller numbers of epochs. This is as expected because CNN is better adapted for our type of image data as it uses assumptions of local connectivity and equivariance.

The bumpiness in the above graphs for the test set is likely due to the ordering in the training dataset. If there are many observations of the same class in a sequence in the training set, the weights of the network will move too far in the direction of classifying this class.

Although the training set is balanced, it is worth shuffling it too. I will do this in the next tasks.

Task 1.2.2¶

I will now scan over a suitable range of the dropout probability (range [0.1, 0.9] in steps of 0.1) to find an optimal value of this dropout probability, using accuracy on the validation set as the measure of performance for this search.

In [27]:
val_accuracies=[]
for x in np.arange(0.1, 1, 0.1):
    model = Sequential([
        Conv2D(8, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
        Conv2D(8, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
        Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
        Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
        MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
        Flatten(),
        Dropout(x),
        Dense(64, activation=keras.layers.LeakyReLU(alpha=0.01), input_shape=(28, 28, 1)),
        Dense(10, activation="softmax")
    ])
    #Load the implemented model and initialize both optimizers and hyperparameters.
    model.compile(optimizer=SGD(learning_rate=0.001, momentum=0), loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
    #Train the model for a total of 40 epochs
    history = model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=40, batch_size=256, verbose=0, validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True)
    val_accuracies.append(history.history['val_accuracy'])

In the graph above the accuracies increase very fast for small dropout probabilities at the beginning and then level off. However, for large dropout probabilities, the accuracies increase gradually at the beginning and then level off.

The dropout technique works by randomly reducing the number of interconnecting neurons within a neural network. We use dropout to minimise overfitting within the trained model because each neuron becomes independently sufficient, in the sense that the neurons within the layers learn weight values that are not based on the cooperation of its neighbouring neurons.

A higher dropout means less training however if you increase dropout past a certain threshold, it results in the model not being able to fit the training data properly.

I chose the optimal dropout probability to be 0.3 because with this the accuracy of the model increases rapidly at the start and levels off at a smaller epoch number. It also makes the model reach a high accuracy of 0.78 after 40 epochs. Finally, it is large enough to significantly make the computation of training the model more efficient.

Task 1.2.3¶

The total number of parameters in the MLP model in Task 1.1.1 can be calculated using the following formula:

$i*h1 + \sum_{k=1}^{n-1}(h_{k}*h_{k+1})+h_{n}*o+\sum_{k=1}^{n}h_{k}+o$

where : $n$ = number of hidden layers $i$ = number of neurons in input layer \ $h_i$ = number of neurons in $i^{th}$ hidden layer \ $o$ = number of neurons in output layer

For our case $n=5$, $i=784$, $h_i=400$ (for $i$ in ${1, 2, 3, 4, 5}$) and $o = 10$. Using the above formula, my MLP in Task 1.1.1 has 959610 parameters.

MLP has the characteristic of fully connected layers. There is redundancy in such high dimensions of the model. Since CNN can account for local connectivity (each filter is panned around the entire image according to a certain size and stride) allows the filter to find and match patterns anywhere in the image. This makes CNN weights smaller and shared and easier to train than MLP.

Can account for local connectivity (each filter is panned around the entire image according to a certain size and stride, allowing the filter to find and match patterns no matter where the pattern is located in a given image). This model can go deeper too than MLP as layers are sparsely connected.

def standardise(X):
    mu = np.mean(X, axis=0)
    std = np.std(X, axis=0)
    std_filled = std.copy()
    std_filled[std==0] = 1.
    Xbar = ((X-mu)/std_filled)
    return Xbar

def pca_function(X,k):

    # create covariance matrix S
    C = 1.0/(len(X)-1) * np.dot(X.T, X) 

    # compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors using the eigsh scipy function
    eigenvalues, eigenvectors = linalg.eigsh(C, k, which="LM", return_eigenvectors=True) 

    # sorting the eigenvectors and eigenvalues from largest to smallest eigenvalue
    sorted_index = np.argsort(eigenvalues)[::-1]
    eigenvalues=eigenvalues[sorted_index]
    eigenvectors=eigenvectors[:,sorted_index ]

    # transform our data
    X_pca = X.dot(eigenvectors)

    return X_pca, eigenvectors, eigenvalues

X_pca, eigenvectors, eigenvalues = pca_function(x_train_1000,784)

def k_means(X_pca, k, max_iter = 15, difference = 0):
    n_samples, n_features = X_pca.shape

    # labels: assign every sample to a cluster at random
    labels = np.random.randint(low=0, high=10, size=n_samples) # randomly generate labels
    X_labels = np.append(X_pca, labels.reshape(-1,1), axis=1)
    centroids = np.zeros((k, n_features))

    # computing the centroids of each of the k clusters
    for i in range(k):
        centroids[i] = np.mean([x for x in X_labels if x[-1]==i], axis=0)[0:2] 

    new_labels = np.zeros(len(X_pca))
    
    # k-means algorithm
    for i in range(max_iter):
        #print('Iteration:', i)
        # distances: between data points and centroids
        distances = np.array([np.linalg.norm(X_pca - c, axis=1) for c in centroids])
        # new_labels: computed by finding centroid with minimal distance
        new_labels = np.argmin(distances, axis=0)

        if (labels==new_labels).all():
            # labels unchanged
            labels = new_labels
            #print('Labels unchanged! Terminating k-means.')
            break
        else:
            # labels changed
            # difference: percentage of changed labels
            difference = np.mean(labels!=new_labels)   
            #print('%4f%% labels changed' % (difference * 100))
            labels = new_labels
            for c in range(k):
                # update centroids by taking the mean over associated data points
                if (labels == c).any():
                    centroids[c] = np.mean(X_pca[labels==c], axis=0) 
                    

    return labels, centroids

def pairwise_distances(points):
    '''
    Args:
        points: A numpy array of points having the shape (N, D), 
          where N is the number of points and D is the number of features.
    Returns:
        A numpy array with shape (N, N) such that the element (i, j) is the computed
        distance between i-th point and j-th point in X.
    '''
    N, D = points.shape
    distance = np.empty((N, N))
    
    # distance matrix will be symmetric, so avoid redundant computations.
    for i in range(N):
        distance[i, i] = 0
        for j in range(i + 1, N):
            d = np.sqrt(np.power(points[i, :] - points[j, :], 2).sum()) 
            distance[i, j] = d
            distance[j, i] = d
            
    return distance

def average_linkage(distances, cluster_assignment, i, j):
    """
    This function computes the average linkage value between two clusters.
    Args:
      distances: A numpy array of pair-wise distances for the given points.
      cluster_assignment: A 1-D numpy array that assigns a cluster id for every point.
      i: the first cluster id.
      j: the second cluster id.
    Returns:
      The average distance between the two given clusters.
    """
    # Select the point indices of the first cluster.
    points_i = np.argwhere(cluster_assignment == i)
    # Select the point indices of the second cluster.
    points_j = np.argwhere(cluster_assignment == j)
    # Form a cartesian product between the indices in i and indices in j.
    pairs = np.array([[element_i.item(), element_j.item()]  for element_i in points_i for element_j in points_j])
    # Select the pair distances between the points in the two clusters from the distances matrix.
    pairs_distance = distances[pairs[:, 0], pairs[:, 1]]
    # Return the average
    return pairs_distance.mean()

def hierarchical_clustering(points, distances, linkage):
    """
    The hierarchical clustering algorithm start with every point as a single cluster and 
    each iteration merges two clusters into one. We may wish to store all the 
    intermediate clustering results with respect to the number of clusters left.

    Args:
     points: A numpy array of points having the shape (N, D), 
          where N is the number of points and D is the number of features.
     distances: A numpy array with shape (N, N) such that the element (i, j) is the computed
        distance between i-th point and j-th point in X.
     linkage: A linkage function from the above to call to compute the linkage values between two clusters.

    Returns:
     A numpy array of shape (N, N) of which each row stores the clustering assignment at each level.
     The first row, i.e. a[0, :], represents the highest level of clustering where all columns have the same index value.
     The second row, i.e. a[1, :], represents all the points assigned into two cluster indices.
     The last row, i.e. a[N - 1, :], represents the points assigned into N - 1 cluster indices.
    """ 
    N, D = points.shape
    assignments = np.zeros((N, N))
    
    # Begin with every point is its own cluster
    current_assignment = np.arange(N)
    
    # The id to be assigned for the next merged cluster
    next_cluster_id = N
    
    # Begin from level (N - 1) to level 1
    for level in range(N - 1, 0, -1):
        cluster_ids = np.unique(current_assignment)
        
        min_d = np.inf
        
        # Initialize the cluster ids to be merged in this iteration.
        cluster_a, cluster_b = (-1, -1) 
        
        # Now find the two clusters that have the minimum distance in between.
        for i in range(cluster_ids.size):
            for j in range(i + 1, cluster_ids.size):
                cluster_i = cluster_ids[i]
                cluster_j = cluster_ids[j]
                d = linkage(distances, current_assignment, cluster_i, cluster_j)
                if d < min_d:
                    min_d = d
                    cluster_a, cluster_b = (cluster_i, cluster_j)
                    
        
        # Merge the two clusters
        current_assignment[(current_assignment == cluster_a) | (current_assignment == cluster_b)] = next_cluster_id
        next_cluster_id += 1
        # Store the current cluster assignment into the assignments array.
        assignments[level, :] = current_assignment
        
    return assignments

def split_cluster(seq):
    split_clusters_list=[]
    for x in set(seq):
        cluster_x = []
        for y in range(len(seq)):
            if seq[y] == x:
                cluster_x.append(y)
        split_clusters_list.append(cluster_x)
    return split_clusters_list

Task 2.2.2¶

Silhouette coefficients isn't defined when there is just one cluster as d2 cant be worked out for any sample. Hence, below I remove such clusters arrangments.

In [62]:
new_fine_to_coarse=fine_to_coarse[:60]

By convention silhouette coefficient for singleton point clusters is 0. Since d1 is 0. A problem with the silhouette is that it is not well defined for 1 element clusters. Because the average distance to other cluster members then is an average over 0 values and thus undefined.

In [63]:
def silhouette_score_curr_level(clustering, F):
    silhouette_coeffs_curr=[]
    for list_index in range(len(clustering)):
        for point_index in clustering[list_index]:
            
            if len(clustering[list_index])==1:
                silhouette_coeffs_curr.append(0)
            else:
                d2=[]
                for cluster in clustering:
                    if point_index in cluster:
                        d1 = np.mean([np.sum(np.square(F[point_index] - F[other_point_index]))**0.5 for other_point_index in cluster if point_index != other_point_index])
                    else:
                        d2.append(np.mean([np.sum(np.square(F[point_index] - F[other_point_index1]))**0.5 for other_point_index1 in cluster]))
                d2=min(d2)
                silhouette_coeffs_curr.append((d2-d1)/max(d2, d1))   
    return np.mean(silhouette_coeffs_curr)

silhouette_score_all_levels=[]     
for level in range(len(new_fine_to_coarse)):
    silhouette_score_all_levels.append(silhouette_score_curr_level(new_fine_to_coarse[level], F))

The Silhouette Score is a measure of the quality of clustering and is defined as the mean Silhouette Coefficient over all samples. The higher the silhouette score the better the quality of clustering in this measure.

# define Laplacian
L = D-A
In [70]:
# computing inverse square root vector of degree
weighted_degree_sqrt = 1.0 / np.sqrt(weighted_degree)

# set a diagonal matrix of the inverse square root of degree
D_inv_sqrt = np.diag(weighted_degree_sqrt)

# define the normalised Laplacian
L_norm = np.eye(A.shape[0]) - D_inv_sqrt.dot(A.dot(D_inv_sqrt))
In [71]:
# return the smallest magnitude eigenvectors and eigenvalues
eigenvals, eigenvecs = linalg.eigsh(L_norm, 2, which="SM", return_eigenvectors=True)
In [72]:

print('The first smallest eigenalue is: {}'.format(eigenvals[0]))

The first smallest eigenalue is: -2.761666221227921e-16
The second smallest eigenalue is: 0.03952455375743408

The first smallest eigenvalue is almost zero. We can assume its non-zero nature is due to a rounding error by my computer. Hence we can view this eigenvalue to be trivially zero. As explained in lecture notes week 10 page 142 lecture notes, this eigenvalue cannot be the solution when looking to minimise cost. Hence our minimal cost is achieved by choosing the second smallest eigenvalue, which is non-zero.

The quality of the bipartition is directly related to the second smallest eigenvalue, which is also called the algebraic connectivity of the graph. My second smallest eigenvector is small enough for me to assume that the graph isn't well connected hence cost of splitting the graph is low (there exists a good bipartition of the graph by the second eigenvector).

From the above table, we can see that Grin, SN4, Topless, Scabs and Trigger to name a few are dolphins with the highest centrality across all three centrality measures.

In Lusseau et al, according to the dendrogram (Fig 4), the dolphins seems to be clustered in 3 groups. Trigger seems to have a central position between groups two and three according to the sociogram (Fig 5) in the paper. Topless is a central individual in group 2, which has 7 dolphins. The dendrogram tells us that Grin, SN4, Topless, Scabs and Trigger belong to the same group 2. Group 2 is generally well connected for each individual within (as it contains many central dolphins) and hence relatively more social. Scabs is known to hold the central position in the female group.

It makes sense that Grin, Scabs, Topless and SN4 score highly on the degree centrality because these dolphins are part of a group 2 with many members in the dendrogram (Fig. 4 in the paper) and also from the sociogram (Fig.5), we can see they have a lot of connections to other dolphins.

Grin and Scabs have high eigenvector centrality because they are connected to other highly central dolphins such as SN4 and to some degree Hook in the sociogram. This means that Grin and Scabs have connections with many other popular dolphins.

In [89]:
sns.set(style='white')
data = {'PageRank centrality':centrality_pagerank, 'Degree centrality':degree, 'Eigenvector centrality':eigenvector.reshape((62,))}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

g = sns.pairplot(df)
plt.show()

We can see that the degree centrality measure is highly positively correlated with PageRank centrality (this is because the PageRank centrality calculation uses the degree matrix). However, degree centrality is correlated with Eigenvector centrality, although not as strongly the combination in the previous sentence.

The centrality rankings differ between the 3 centrality measures because they each measure the importance of a node from a different perspective and further provides relevant analytical information about the graph and its nodes. In Eigenvector centrality, higher importance is given to nodes that are themselves connected to other highly central nodes whereas in Degree centrality higher importance is given to nodes that are connected to a large number of other nodes. Finally, in PageRank centrality, nodes, where many searches will reside with higher probability, are given high importance. Therefore PageRank is more useful with directed graphs unlike our undirected graph.
